article.description: Detroit held Connecticut scoreless for more than 11 minutes of the second half, and used a 21-point run to post an easy 66-50 victory Tuesday night.
article.headline: 21-0 run propels Detroit to victory
article.linkText: Shock defense stuns Sun in second half
article.story: AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- The Detroit Shock are known around the WNBA for their run-and-gun offense. On Tuesday, they showed they can play at the other end of the court, as well. The Shock held the Connecticut Sun scoreless for more than 11 minutes of the second half, and used a 21-point run to post an easy 66-50 victory. "Obviously, when you hold a team scoreless for that long, some of it comes from them missing shots," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "But the key was that we made them take jump shots; they didn't get a single easy shot in that stretch. Our players were all over the place on defense." Detroit came into the game having lost three of four, including a 31-point loss at Indiana on Sunday. "We knew we had to pick things up on defense," said rookie Cheryl Ford. "That had really let us down in the last two games, but we did a great job tonight." Swin Cash scored 13 points and Ford added 11 as Detroit moved a half-game ahead of Charlotte atop the Eastern Conference. The Shock and Sting play at Charlotte on Thursday. "We've got to get that one," Ford said. "They've beaten us twice here already, so we really need to win one down there." Connecticut saw its three-game winning streak end. "That was just a bad basketball game," said Sun coach Mike Thibault. "There's no other way to put it." During Detroit's 21-0 run, the Sun missed 17 straight shots before Shannon Johnson made a layup with 5:24 to play. Deanna Nolan had six points in the surge, while Kedra Holland-Corn added five. "Teams are doing everything they can to take Deanna away from our offense, but she's still getting us points off steals," Laimbeer said. "She's one of the best defensive guards in this league." Nykesha Sales led the Sun with 15 points, but no one else reached double figures. Johnson scored just nine points, six under her season average. "We had a lot of players taking good shots, but the ball just wouldn't go in," Sales said. "It was just one of those nights -- we couldn't score and we couldn't get any stops, either." Detroit jumped to a 13-2 lead, but the Sun narrowed the gap to 38-34 at the half. The margin was still four, 42-38, with less than 17 minutes to play, but the Sun collapsed. "There's no magic formula to stop it," Thibault said. "There's just no chance when you shoot the ball that badly." Notes: WNBA president Val Ackerman attended the game and met with the media before tip-off. ... Sales committed a technical foul and a flagrant foul in the first half. ... Nolan was scoreless in the first half, and has scored just 14 points in three games since making the All-Star team. ... Connecticut missed 26 of its first 30 shots in the second half. ... Detroit improved to 3-0 against the Sun this season. The teams play for the final time on Aug. 5 at Connecticut.
